      <title>Social experiment, Part II</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          In <xref ref="socExpP1">Exercise</xref>, we encountered a scenario where researchers were evaluating the impact of the way someone is dressed against the actions of people around them. In that exercise, researchers may have believed that dressing provocatively may reduce the chance of bystander intervention. One might be tempted to use a one-sided hypothesis test for this study. Discuss the drawbacks of doing so in 1-3 sentences.
        </p>
